103
00:11:39,076 --> 00:11:51,563
[SPEAKER_20]: As I've mentioned previously, I'm very concerned about maintaining a healthy community of predominantly owner-occupied homes, as that is how we've come to be a vibrant, working, and middle-class neighborhood that engages with and supports each other.

104
00:11:52,343 --> 00:12:00,985
[SPEAKER_20]: Having done the research, I find that from the 40s and 60s and even the early 2000s, the United States federal government launched programs that encouraged home ownership.

105
00:12:01,525 --> 00:12:03,945
[SPEAKER_20]: This is essentially what birthed the middle class.

106
00:12:04,425 --> 00:12:13,627
[SPEAKER_20]: The primary goals behind these policies were to build household or multi-generational wealth, to stabilize the economy, and to foster civic engagement.

107
00:12:14,107 --> 00:12:14,607
[SPEAKER_20]: It worked.

108
00:12:14,927 --> 00:12:18,528
[SPEAKER_20]: I'm here, like so many others in this room, because these policies worked.

109
00:12:19,340 --> 00:12:27,270
[SPEAKER_20]: My biggest concern regarding our neighborhoods currently is that investors, not homeowners, have been purchasing much of the inventory as it becomes available.

110
00:12:28,271 --> 00:12:38,824
[SPEAKER_20]: For example, in the last few years, at least six of the formerly owner-occupied homes within a two-and-a-half block radius of my home have been purchased by investors not living here.

111
00:12:39,426 --> 00:12:42,467
[SPEAKER_20]: They've created guest homes, Airbnbs, rentals for students.

112
00:12:42,667 --> 00:12:45,028
[SPEAKER_20]: At least three of them remain empty most of the year.

113
00:12:45,708 --> 00:12:52,891
[SPEAKER_20]: This undermines our ability to coalesce as a community and gain the financial and relational stability owner-occupied housing provides.

114
00:12:53,431 --> 00:12:56,853
[SPEAKER_20]: This is an example of the current K economy, which is gutting the middle class.

115
00:12:57,671 --> 00:13:01,413
